Desert Ecology

For this assignment, we are going to use a modified data set on desert ecology. The data are from: S. K. Morgan Ernest, Thomas J. Valone, and James H. Brown. 2009. Long-term monitoring and experimental manipulation of a Chihuahuan Desert ecosystem near Portal, Arizona, USA. Ecology 90:1708.

  1. What is the proportion of taxa included in this study? Show a table and plot that reflects this count.
deserts %>% 
  tabyl(taxa)
##     taxa     n      percent
##     Bird   450 0.0129362387
##   Rabbit    75 0.0021560398
##  Reptile    14 0.0004024608
##   Rodent 34247 0.9845052607
deserts %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=taxa, fill=taxa))+
  geom_bar()+
  scale_y_log10()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1), plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1), hjust = 0.5))+
  labs(title = "Amount of Taxa", x = "Taxa", y="Count (log10)")

  1. What is the relationship between weight and hindfoot length? Consider whether or not over plotting is an issue.
deserts %>% 
  filter(weight != "NA", hindfoot_length != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=weight, y= hindfoot_length))+
  geom_point(na.rm=T)+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1), plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1), hjust = 0.5))+
  labs(title = "Hindfoot Length vs Weight", x = "Weight", y="Hindfoot Length")

This plot is very messy! So many points on the graph are overlapping, this is not nice to look at. Over plotting is definitely an issue here!

deserts %>% 
  filter(weight != "NA", hindfoot_length != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=weight, y= hindfoot_length))+
  geom_jitter(na.rm = T, size = 0.2, alpha = 0.4)+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1), plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1), hjust = 0.5))+
  labs(title = "Hindfoot Length vs Weight", x = "Weight", y="Hindfoot Length")

This makes it a little better but there are still some over plotting issues

  mutate(weight_to_hindfoot_ratio = (weight/hindfoot_length))
